    "route": "/education/ai_systems/computer_vision",
    "file": "content/education/ai_systems/computer_vision.md",
    "content": "# Computer Vision\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nComputer vision enables AI to interpret visual market data such as charts, order-book heatmaps, and depth ladders.\n\n### Origin\nAdvanced rapidly after convolutional neural networks in 2012; applied to finance with the rise of high-resolution market data visualization.\n\n### Why It Matters\nMany market signals are visual patterns that traditional numerical models miss.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nModels process candlestick charts, volume profiles, and order-flow visualizations to detect patterns and anomalies.\n\n### How It Behaves\nExcels at spotting recurring formations but can be fooled by novel regime shifts.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Pattern recognition confidence\n- False-positive rates on historical regimes\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nProprietary trading firms use vision models for tape reading and microstructure analysis.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Automated chart pattern detection\n- Order-book visualization anomaly alerts\n- Cross-asset visual correlation mapping\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Technical Agent**: Processes live chart and heatmap imagery.\n- **Liquidity Agent**: Interprets depth ladder visuals for hidden liquidity.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nComputer vision turns visual market intuition into scalable, repeatable intelligence.\n\n## Related Topics\n- neural_networks.md\n- embeddings.md\n"
