    "file": "content/education/asset_classes/cash_equivalents.md",
    "content": "# Cash Equivalents\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nCash equivalents are highly liquid, short-term instruments that preserve capital.\n\n### Origin\nTreasury bills became the institutional standard after the 1970s.\n\n### Why It Matters\nCash equivalents serve as dry powder and the ultimate risk-off asset.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nInstruments include T-bills and money-market funds tied to policy rates.\n\n### How It Behaves\nReal yields turn negative during easing.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Short-term Treasury yields\n- Reverse repo usage\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nInstitutions manage cash equivalents for liquidity and policy implementation.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Liquidity buffers\n- Collateral in repo markets\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Liquidity Agent**: Monitors cash flows as risk appetite indicators.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nCash equivalents are the tactical reserve of institutional portfolios.\n\n## Related Topics\n- fixed_income.md\n- liquidity.md\n"
