    "route": "/education/asset_classes/fixed_income",
    "file": "content/education/asset_classes/fixed_income.md",
    "content": "# Fixed Income\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nFixed income securities are debt instruments that provide periodic interest payments.\n\n### Origin\nGovernment bonds became the global benchmark after World War II.\n\n### Why It Matters\nFixed income serves as the risk-free benchmark and portfolio stabilizer.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nBond prices move inversely to yields. Duration measures interest-rate sensitivity.\n\n### How It Behaves\nFixed income exhibits negative correlation to equities in flight-to-quality regimes.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Yield curve shape\n- Credit spreads\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nInstitutions manage fixed-income portfolios for liability matching.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Duration hedging\n- Credit versus rates relative value\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Macro Agent**: Interprets yield curve signals.\n- **Risk Agent**: Models duration risk.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nFixed income is the foundational pricing mechanism for all risk assets.\n\n## Related Topics\n- equities.md\n- derivatives.md\n"
