    "file": "content/education/asset_classes/hybrid_securities.md",
    "content": "# Hybrid Securities\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nHybrid securities combine debt and equity features such as convertible bonds.\n\n### Origin\nConvertibles emerged in the 19th century.\n\n### Why It Matters\nHybrids bridge fixed income and equity allocations.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nPricing reflects credit risk and the embedded equity option.\n\n### How It Behaves\nHybrids behave like bonds when out-of-the-money and like equity when in-the-money.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Conversion premium\n- Embedded option Greeks\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nHedge funds exploit mispricings while corporates issue hybrids for lower-cost financing.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Convertible arbitrage\n- Mezzanine financing\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Technical Agent**: Monitors delta and gamma exposure.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nHybrid securities provide sophisticated risk-reward engineering.\n\n## Related Topics\n- derivatives.md\n- fixed_income.md\n"
