    "title": "Bridges",
    "category": "blockchain",
    "slug": "bridges",
    "route": "/education/blockchain/bridges",
    "file": "content/education/blockchain/bridges.md",
    "content": "# Bridges\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nBridges are protocols that transfer assets or data between different blockchains.\n\n### Origin\nBridges expanded rapidly after 2021 as multi-chain ecosystems grew and users needed to move assets between Ethereum, Layer 2 networks, and alternative Layer 1s.\n\n### Why It Matters\nBridges enable capital mobility and composability across fragmented blockchain networks.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nBridges use lock-and-mint, burn-and-release, or liquidity pool models. Security relies on validators, economic incentives, smart contracts, or cryptographic proofs.\n\n### How It Behaves\nBridges are frequent targets of exploits because they hold large value and depend on complex trust assumptions. Bridge flows can also reveal capital rotation between ecosystems.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Total value bridged\n- Bridge TVL and utilization\n- Security incident history\n- Cross-chain flow volume\n- Validator or relayer structure\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nInstitutions use audited, permissioned, or highly reputable bridges for cross-chain treasury and tokenized asset movement. Risk controls often restrict bridge exposure.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Multi-chain portfolio management\n- Cross-chain collateral rebalancing\n- Arbitrage between ecosystems\n- Tokenized asset distribution\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Liquidity Agent**: Tracks bridge flows and arbitrage opportunities.\n- **Risk Agent**: Scores bridge security and counterparty assumptions.\n- **Portfolio Agent**: Adjusts chain exposure based on flow migration.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nBridges are the connective infrastructure of multi-chain finance and a critical point of systemic risk.\n\n## Related Topics\n- layer1_vs_layer2.md\n- defi.md\n- stablecoins.md\n"
