    "title": "Prop Trading",
    "category": "institutional",
    "slug": "prop_trading",
    "route": "/education/institutional/prop_trading",
    "file": "content/education/institutional/prop_trading.md",
    "content": "# Prop Trading\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nProprietary trading is trading an institution’s own capital for direct profit.\n\n### Origin\nProp trading was a major profit center until the Volcker Rule.\n\n### Why It Matters\nProp trading drives market liquidity and price discovery.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nProp desks use leverage and quantitative models across asset classes.\n\n### How It Behaves\nPerformance is variable and can create systemic risk when leveraged positions unwind.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Value-at-risk limits\n- Return on equity\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nProp trading has migrated to hedge funds and specialized firms post-Volcker.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Statistical arbitrage\n- Macro directional trading\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Risk Agent**: Monitors firm-wide prop exposure.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nProprietary trading remains a core driver of market liquidity.\n\n## Related Topics\n- quant_funds.md\n"
