    "title": "Dollar System",
    "category": "macro",
    "slug": "dollar_system",
    "route": "/education/macro/dollar_system",
    "file": "content/education/macro/dollar_system.md",
    "content": "# Dollar System\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nThe dollar system is the global network of dollar-denominated trade, reserves, and financial flows.\n\n### Origin\nThe dollar became dominant after Bretton Woods in 1944.\n\n### Why It Matters\nDollar system mechanics determine global liquidity and U.S. economic privilege.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nThe dollar’s reserve status creates structural demand through trade invoicing and reserve holdings.\n\n### How It Behaves\nThe system is resilient but sensitive to U.S. policy and geopolitical shifts.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Dollar share in global reserves\n- SWIFT transaction shares\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nCentral banks manage dollar reserves with liquidity and safety constraints.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Dollar strength forecasting\n- De-dollarization monitoring\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Macro Agent**: Tracks dollar system dynamics.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nThe dollar system is the backbone of global finance and U.S. economic influence.\n\n## Related Topics\n- reserve_currency.md\n"
