    "title": "Fiscal Policy",
    "category": "macro",
    "slug": "fiscal_policy",
    "route": "/education/macro/fiscal_policy",
    "file": "content/education/macro/fiscal_policy.md",
    "content": "# Fiscal Policy\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nFiscal policy is government spending and taxation used to influence economic activity.\n\n### Origin\nModern fiscal policy was shaped by Keynes in the 1930s.\n\n### Why It Matters\nFiscal policy can provide powerful stimulus independent of monetary policy.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nExpansionary fiscal policy increases deficits; contractionary policy reduces them.\n\n### How It Behaves\nFiscal policy is most effective when monetary policy is accommodative.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Budget deficit\n- Fiscal impulse\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nInstitutions position for fiscal expansions through risk assets.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Fiscal stimulus trade implementation\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Macro Agent**: Incorporates fiscal impulse into forecasts.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nFiscal policy is a powerful but politically constrained tool.\n\n## Related Topics\n- monetary_policy.md\n"
