    "title": "Quantitative Easing",
    "category": "macro",
    "slug": "quantitative_easing",
    "route": "/education/macro/quantitative_easing",
    "file": "content/education/macro/quantitative_easing.md",
    "content": "# Quantitative Easing\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nQuantitative easing is central bank purchase of securities to inject liquidity.\n\n### Origin\nFirst implemented by the Federal Reserve in 2008.\n\n### Why It Matters\nQE is the primary non-conventional tool when rates are near zero.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nQE expands the central bank balance sheet and lowers long-term rates.\n\n### How It Behaves\nQE compresses risk premia and supports asset prices.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Central bank balance sheet size\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nInstitutions front-run QE announcements.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Duration extension trades\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Macro Agent**: Tracks QE liquidity transmission.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nQuantitative easing is central bank liquidity injection at scale.\n\n## Related Topics\n- quantitative_tightening.md\n"
