    "slug": "quantitative_tightening",
    "route": "/education/macro/quantitative_tightening",
    "file": "content/education/macro/quantitative_tightening.md",
    "content": "# Quantitative Tightening\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nQuantitative tightening is the reduction of a central bank’s balance sheet.\n\n### Origin\nFirst implemented by the Federal Reserve in 2017.\n\n### Why It Matters\nQT removes liquidity and can tighten financial conditions.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nBalance-sheet runoff reduces bank reserves.\n\n### How It Behaves\nMarkets often price QT in advance.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Central bank balance-sheet contraction pace\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nInstitutions reduce risk exposure during QT.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Defensive positioning\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Macro Agent**: Monitors QT transmission.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nQuantitative tightening is the deliberate withdrawal of central bank liquidity.\n\n## Related Topics\n- quantitative_easing.md\n"
