    "title": "Volatility Modeling",
    "category": "quant",
    "slug": "volatility_modeling",
    "route": "/education/quant/volatility_modeling",
    "file": "content/education/quant/volatility_modeling.md",
    "content": "# Volatility Modeling\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nVolatility modeling forecasts the magnitude of price fluctuations over time.\n\n### Origin\nGARCH models were introduced in the 1980s.\n\n### Why It Matters\nAccurate volatility forecasts are essential for risk management and option pricing.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nModels capture volatility clustering and mean reversion.\n\n### How It Behaves\nVolatility is persistent and exhibits fat tails.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Realized versus implied volatility\n- Volatility term structure\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nRisk departments use volatility models for daily VaR and option pricing.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Dynamic risk limits\n- Volatility surface construction\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Risk Agent**: Incorporates volatility forecasts into portfolio risk.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nVolatility modeling is central to quantitative risk management.\n\n## Related Topics\n- garch_models.md\n"
