    "title": "Counterparty Risk",
    "category": "risk_management",
    "slug": "counterparty_risk",
    "route": "/education/risk_management/counterparty_risk",
    "file": "content/education/risk_management/counterparty_risk.md",
    "content": "# Counterparty Risk\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nCounterparty risk is the risk that the other party in a transaction defaults.\n\n### Origin\nCounterparty risk gained prominence after Lehman’s 2008 failure.\n\n### Why It Matters\nCounterparty failure can cascade through the financial system.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nCounterparty risk is mitigated by collateral, netting, and central clearing.\n\n### How It Behaves\nRisk spikes during market stress when counterparties are most likely to default.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Credit default swap spreads on counterparties\n- Collateral coverage ratios\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nInstitutions diversify counterparties and use central clearing where possible.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Prime broker diversification\n- Collateral optimization\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Risk Agent**: Monitors counterparty exposure in real time.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nCounterparty risk is a systemic amplifier during crises.\n\n## Related Topics\n- systemic_risk.md\n"
