    "slug": "tail_risk",
    "route": "/education/risk_management/tail_risk",
    "file": "content/education/risk_management/tail_risk.md",
    "content": "# Tail Risk\n\n## Beginner Level\n\n### What Is It?\nTail risk is the risk of extreme, low-probability events in the tails of the return distribution.\n\n### Origin\nTail risk became central after 1987 and 2008 crises.\n\n### Why It Matters\nTail events can dominate long-term returns.\n\n## Intermediate Level\n\n### Market Mechanics\nTail risk is measured by expected shortfall and scenario analysis.\n\n### How It Behaves\nTail risk is often underestimated because historical data contains few extremes.\n\n### Key Data to Watch\n- Expected shortfall at 99.9%\n- Portfolio kurtosis\n\n## Advanced Level\n\n### Institutional Behavior\nInstitutions maintain explicit tail-risk hedging programs.\n\n### Professional Use Cases\n- Tail-risk hedging overlays\n\n### AI Interpretation in Systems Like Arkhe\n- **Risk Agent**: Simulates synthetic tail events.\n\n### Key Takeaways\nTail risk management is essential for institutional survival.\n\n## Related Topics\n- black_swans.md\n"
